Q1 — RAG only: Policy lookup
Query: "What does our SLA say about uptime requirements?"
================================================================================

Steps:
  [Tool Call] query_vendor_knowledge_base({'query': 'uptime requirements in SLA'})

  [Tool Result] query_vendor_knowledge_base:
    [Source: acme_corp_contract.txt]
    SECTION 4 — SERVICE LEVEL AGREEMENT
    4.1 Uptime Commitment
    Vendor shall maintain a monthly Service Availability of not less than 99.5%
    ("Uptime Commitment"), measured on a calendar-month basis. A 99.5% monthly
    uptime commitment permits a maximum of 219 minutes of unexcused downtime per
    calendar month.

    [Source: sla_policy.txt]
    At 99.5%, the maximum permitted unexcused downtime per calendar month is 219
    minutes (approximately 3 hours and 39 minutes).

    [Source: escalation_policy.txt]
    5.3 Performance Improvement Plan (PIP)
    Vendors subject to a Tier 3 escalation shall be placed on a formal Performance
    Improvement Plan (PIP) for a minimum of ninety (90) calendar days. During the
    PIP period:
      - Vendor performance shall be reviewed bi-weekly by the VMO;
      - Vendor must meet 100% of scheduled deliveries for three consecutive months
        to be removed from PIP status;

Answer:
  According to our SLA, the uptime commitment is a minimum of 99.5% on a
  calendar-month basis, allowing up to 219 minutes of unexcused downtime per
  month. If this threshold is breached, vendors may be placed on a Performance
  Improvement Plan (PIP) for at least 90 days, during which they must meet all
  scheduled deliveries for three consecutive months to avoid further penalties.

  The SLA also outlines that vendors subject to Tier 3 escalations will be placed
  on a PIP and their performance will be reviewed bi-weekly by the VMO.


